<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-150-626  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 150 626.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Feb 12 1990 v7 n6 p46(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>FaxGate gives networked Macs fax abilities within E-mail. (productannouncement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>O'Regan, Rob.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Solutions Inc. (product introduction).andO;Product:   FaxGate (Computer network software) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionCommunications software.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Rob O'ReganandM;Solutions Inc. recently began shipping new gateway software that allowsnetworked Macintosh users to send and receive faxes from within theirelectronic-mail applications.andM;The company's new FaxGate resides on an AppleTalk or compatible network mailserver, and works with Solutions' BackFax communications software and acompatible fax modem.andM;The software allows users of Microsoft Corp.'s Microsoft Mail to transmitfacsimiles to any Group III fax machine or compatible fax modem in the sameway that they would send an E-mail message, according to Mary Evslin,president of the Williston, Vt., company.andM;Both FaxGate and BackFax run in the background, allowing users to work intheir applications while a fax is being transmitted, she said.andM;The Portsmouth, N.H., office of Liberty Mutual Insurance has successfullybeta tested FaxGate as a means to streamline a cumbersome manual method offaxing documents created on its Macintoshes, according to Scott Joy, aresearch associate with the firm.andM;&quot;Generally, we would create our fax using a word processor, print it out,then run down to the administration department to send it,&quot; Joy explained.andO;&quot;[Now] we can create the fax on the Mac and immediately send it, withoutusing physical copy at all.&quot;andM;The insurance office is using FaxGate and BackFax on an AppleTalk networkwith Microsoft Mail and Apple Computer Inc.'s AppleFax fax modem.andM;The new software also includes a version of Solutions' SuperGlue utilitysoftware, which enables users to send fully formatted documents to anelectronic mailbox or fax machine, according to Evslin.andM;The FaxGate version of SuperGlue, called MailMaker, lets Mac users view orprint files created with a specific database or word-processing application,for example, without having that application on their computer.andM;FaxGate costs $395 for a copy of the network server software and a MailMakerfive-user starter kit.andP;  Single-user MailMaker add-in packs cost $40.andM;Versions of FaxGate that work with CE Software's QuickMail 2.0 and TOPS'Inbox electronic-mail software are scheduled for release this spring,according to Solutions officials.andM;BackFax works with fax modems from Apple, Orchid Technology, Circuit ResearchCorp., Prometheus and Relisys.andM;Solutions Inc. can be reached at (802) 865-9220.andO;</TEXT></DOC>